\subsection{Gloss abbreviations}

Linguists standardly use glosses for indicating the meaning of pieces
of words (morphemes). One common set of glosses is the Leipzig Glosses. However, Leipzig Glosses are not universially used for several reasons including: 

\begin{itemize}
\item some authors have established their own tradition within their works which they started prior to the release of the Leipzig Glosses,
\item they are not comprehensive, and
\item they are not throetically sufficent for some linguists.
\end{itemize}

 \XLP{} approaches this by providing built in access to Leipzig Glosses, but also allowing the author to define a set of
abbreviations and their definitions.  When producing the output,
\XLP{} creates hyperlinks between the abbreviation and its
definition. This allows for the automatic generation of a table of abbreviations used.

